{
  "slide": 2,
  "duration": 71.02,
  "text": "Historically, there is an accountability gap. And what is that accountability gap? So the people who execute the hygiene and sanitation protocols on site are ultimately not the people held accountable. See, we delegate this responsibility to them, but ultimately cannot delegate accountability for anything going wrong. Without continuous visibility, leadership relies on periodic reports and site visits to assess and mitigate any such risks. Site managers and supervisors do the work, compiles all the reports, but otherwise top management holds the ultimate accountability. Today, that accountability relies on our trust on the people on site, as it should be, but in our industry, that trust requires that extra burden of proof. And top management can only manage what they know.",
